{"title_page": "March 27", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[1309]] &ndash; [[Pope Clement V]] imposes [[excommunication]] and [[interdict]]ion on Venice, and a general prohibition of all commercial intercourse with Venice, which had seized on [[Ferrara]], a papal fiefdom.\n*[[1329]] &ndash; [[Pope John XXII]] issues his ''In Agro Dominico'' condemning some writings of [[Meister Eckhart]] as heretical.\n*[[1513]] &ndash; Spanish explorer [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n]] reaches the northern end of [[The Bahamas]] on his first voyage to Florida.\n*[[1625]] &ndash; [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] becomes King of England, Scotland and Ireland as well as claiming the title [[English claims to the French throne|King of France]].\n*[[1782]] &ndash; [[Charles Watson-Wentworth, 2nd Marquess of Rockingham]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]].\n*[[1794]] &ndash; The [[Federal government of the United States|United States Government]] establishes a permanent [[United States Navy|navy]] and authorizes the building of [[Original six frigates of the United States Navy|six frigates]].\n*[[1809]] &ndash; [[Peninsular War]]: A combined [[First French Empire|Franco]]-[[Duchy of Warsaw|Polish]] force defeats the Spanish in the [[Battle of Ciudad Real]].\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[War of 1812]]: In central [[Alabama]], U.S. forces under General [[Andrew Jackson]] defeat the [[Creek (people)|Creek]] at the [[Battle of Horseshoe Bend (1814)|Battle of Horseshoe Bend]].\n*[[1836]] &ndash; [[Texas Revolution]]: On the orders of General [[Antonio L\u00f3pez de Santa Anna]], the Mexican army [[Goliad massacre|massacres]] 342 Texas POWs at [[Goliad, Texas]].\n*[[1866]] &ndash; President of the United States of America [[Andrew Johnson]] vetoes the [[Civil Rights Act of 1866]]. His veto is overridden by Congress and the bill passes into law on April 9. \n*[[1871]] &ndash; The [[1871 England versus Scotland rugby union match|first]] international [[rugby football]] match, when [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] defeats [[England national rugby union team|England]] in [[Edinburgh]] at [[Raeburn Place]].\n*[[1884]] &ndash; A mob in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], attacks members of a jury which had returned a verdict of [[manslaughter]] in what was seen as a clear case of [[murder]]; over the next few days the mob would [[Cincinnati riots of 1884|riot and eventually destroy the courthouse]].\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Geronimo]], [[Apache]] warrior, surrenders to the U.S. Army, ending the main phase of the [[Apache Wars]].\n*[[1899]] &ndash; [[Emilio Aguinaldo]] leads [[Philippine Revolutionary Army|Filipino forces]] for the only time during the [[Philippine\u2013American War]] at the [[Battle of Marilao River]].\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Typhoid Mary]], the first [[Asymptomatic carrier|healthy carrier]] of disease ever identified in the United States is put in [[quarantine]] for the second time, where she would remain for the rest of her life.\n*[[1918]] &ndash; The National Council of [[Bessarabia]] proclaims [[Union of Bessarabia with Romania|union]] with the [[Kingdom of Romania]].\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Second Sino-Japanese War]]: The [[Battle of Taierzhuang]] begins, resulting several weeks later in the war's first major Chinese victory over Japan.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Yugoslav Air Force]] officers topple the [[Axis powers|pro-Axis]] government in a [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|bloodless coup]].\n*[[1943]] &ndash; World War II: [[Battle of the Komandorski Islands]]: In the [[Aleutian Islands]] the battle begins when United States Navy forces intercept Japanese attempting to reinforce a [[garrison]] at [[Kiska]].\n*[[1945]] &ndash; World War II: [[Operation Starvation]], the aerial mining of Japan's ports and waterways begins. Argentina [[Argentina during World War II|declares war]] on the Axis Powers.\n*[[1958]] &ndash; [[Nikita Khrushchev]] becomes [[Chairman]] of the [[Council of Ministers of the Soviet Union]].\n*[[1964]] &ndash; The [[1964 Alaska earthquake|Good Friday earthquake]], the most powerful earthquake recorded in [[North America]]n history at a [[moment magnitude scale|magnitude]] of 9.2 strikes [[Southcentral Alaska]], killing 125 people and inflicting massive damage to the city of [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]].\n*[[1975]] &ndash; Construction of the [[Trans-Alaska Pipeline System]] begins.\n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Tenerife airport disaster]]: Two [[Boeing 747]] [[airliner]]s collide on a foggy runway on [[Tenerife]] in the [[Canary Islands]], killing 583 (all 248 on [[KLM]] and 335 on [[Pan Am]]). Sixty-one survived on the Pan Am flight. This is the deadliest aviation accident in history.\n*[[1980]] &ndash; The Norwegian oil platform ''[[Alexander L. Kielland (platform)|Alexander L. Kielland]]'' collapses in the [[North Sea]], killing 123 of its crew of 212.\n*  1980   &ndash; [[Silver Thursday]]: A steep fall in [[silver]] prices, resulting from [[Nelson Bunker Hunt|the Hunt Brothers]] attempting to [[corner the market]] in silver, leads to panic on commodity and [[futures exchange]]s.\n*[[1981]] &ndash; The [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] movement in Poland stages a [[1981 warning strike in Poland|warning strike]], in which at least 12 million Poles walk off their jobs for four hours.\n*[[1986]] &ndash; A [[car bomb]] explodes outside [[Russell Street bombing|Russell Street Police HQ]] in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]], killing one police officer and injuring 21 people.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; The United States begins broadcasting anti-[[Fidel Castro|Castro]] propaganda to [[Cuba]] on [[TV Mart\u00ed]].\n*[[1993]] &ndash; [[Jiang Zemin]] is appointed [[President of the People's Republic of China]].\n*  1993   &ndash; Italian former minister and [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democracy]] leader [[Giulio Andreotti]] is accused of [[Sicilian Mafia|mafia]] allegiance by the tribunal of [[Palermo]].\n*[[1998]] &ndash; The [[Food and Drug Administration]] approves [[Viagra]] for use as a treatment for male [[impotence]], the first pill to be approved for this condition in the United States.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Kosovo War]]: An American [[Lockheed F-117A Nighthawk]] is [[1999 F-117A shootdown|shot down]] by a Yugoslav SAM, the first and only Nighthawk to be lost in combat.\n*[[2000]] &ndash; A [[Phillips explosion of 2000|Phillips Petroleum plant explosion]] in [[Pasadena, Texas]] kills one person and injures 71 others.\n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[Passover massacre]]: A [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] [[suicide bomber]] kills 29 people at a [[Passover seder]] in [[Netanya]], Israel.\n*  2002   &ndash; [[Nanterre massacre]]: In [[Nanterre]], France, a gunman opens fire at the end of a town council meeting, resulting in the deaths of eight councilors; 19 other people are injured.\n*[[2004]] &ndash; {{HMS|Scylla|F71|6}}, a decommissioned [[Leander-class frigate|''Leander''-class frigate]], is sunk as an artificial reef off [[Cornwall]], the first of its kind in Europe.\n*[[2009]] &ndash; The dam forming [[Situ Gintung]], an artificial lake in [[Indonesia]], fails, killing at least 99 people.\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Government of the Philippines|Philippines]] signs a [[Comprehensive Agreement on the Bangsamoro|peace accord]] with the largest Muslim rebel group, the [[Moro Islamic Liberation Front]], ending decades of [[Moro insurgency in the Philippines|conflict]].\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabab]] militants [[Makka al-Mukarama hotel attack|attack and temporarily occupy]] a [[Mogadishu]] hotel leaving at least 20 people dead.\n*[[2016]] &ndash; A [[2016 Lahore suicide bombing|suicide blast]] in [[Gulshan-e-Iqbal Park]], [[Lahore]] claims over 70 lives and leaves almost 300 others injured. The target of the bombing are [[Christianity in Pakistan|Christians]] celebrating [[Easter]].\n*[[2020]] &ndash; [[North Macedonia]] becomes the 30th member of [[NATO]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_174589.htm|title=North Macedonia joins NATO as 30th Ally|website=NATO}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n<!-- Please do not add yourself to the list of births -->\n* [[972]] &ndash; [[Robert II of France|Robert II]], king of France (d. 1031)\n*[[1401]] &ndash; [[Albert III, Duke of Bavaria|Albert III]], duke of Bavaria (d. 1460)\n*[[1416]] &ndash; [[Francis of Paola]], Italian friar and saint, founded [[Order of the Minims]] (d. 1507)\n*[[1546]] &ndash; [[Johannes Piscator]], German theologian (d. 1625)\n*[[1627]] &ndash; [[Stephen Fox]], English politician (d. 1716)\n*[[1676]] &ndash; [[Francis II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi]], Hungarian prince (b. 1676)\n*[[1679]] &ndash; [[Domenico Lalli]], Italian poet and librettist (d. 1741)\n*[[1681]] &ndash; [[Joaqu\u00edn Fern\u00e1ndez de Portocarrero]], Spanish-Italian cardinal (d. 1760)\n*[[1702]] &ndash; [[Johann Ernst Eberlin]], German organist and composer (d. 1762)\n*[[1710]] &ndash; [[Joseph Abaco]], Belgian cellist and composer (d. 1805)\n*[[1712]] &ndash; [[Claude Bourgelat]], French surgeon and author (d. 1779)\n*[[1714]] &ndash; [[Francesco Antonio Zaccaria]], Italian historian and theologian (d. 1795)\n*[[1724]] &ndash; [[Jane Colden]], American botanist and author (d. 1766)\n*[[1745]] &ndash; [[Lindley Murray]], American-English Quaker and grammarian (d. 1826)\n*[[1746]] &ndash; [[Michael Bruce (poet)|Michael Bruce]], Scottish poet and composer (d. 1767)\n*  1746   &ndash; [[Carlo Buonaparte]], Corsican-French lawyer and politician (d. 1785)\n*[[1765]] &ndash; [[Franz Xaver von Baader]], German philosopher and theologian (d. 1841)\n*[[1781]] &ndash; [[Alexander Vostokov]], Estonian-Russian philologist and academic (d. 1864)\n*[[1784]] &ndash; [[S\u00e1ndor K\u0151r\u00f6si Csoma]], Hungarian philologist, orientalist, and author (d. 1842)\n*[[1785]] &ndash; [[Louis XVII of France]] (d. 1795)\n*[[1797]] &ndash; [[Alfred de Vigny]], French author, poet, and playwright (d. 1863)\n*[[1801]] &ndash; [[Alexander Barrow]], American lawyer and politician (d. 1846)\n*[[1802]] &ndash; [[Charles-Mathias Simons]], German-Luxembourger jurist and politician, 3rd [[Prime Minister of Luxembourg]] (d. 1874)\n*[[1809]] &ndash; [[Georges-Eug\u00e8ne Haussmann]], French engineer, urban planner, and politician (d. 1891)\n*[[1811]] &ndash; [[Edward William Cooke]], English painter and illustrator (d. 1880)\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Charles Mackay (author)|Charles Mackay]], Scottish journalist, anthologist, and author (d. 1889)\n*[[1820]] &ndash; [[Edward Augustus Inglefield]], English admiral and explorer (d. 1894)\n*[[1822]] &ndash; [[Henri Murger]], French novelist and poet (d. 1861)\n*[[1824]] &ndash; [[Virginia Minor]], American women's suffrage activist (d. 1894)\n*[[1839]] &ndash; [[John Ballance]], Irish-New Zealand journalist and politician, 14th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. 1893)\n*[[1843]] &ndash; [[George Frederick Leycester Marshall]], English colonel and entomologist (d. 1934)\n*[[1844]] &ndash; [[Adolphus Greely]], American general and explorer, [[Medal of Honor]] recipient (d. 1935)\n*[[1845]] &ndash; [[Wilhelm R\u00f6ntgen]], German physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1923)\n*  1845   &ndash; [[Jakob Sverdrup (politician)|Jakob Sverdrup]], Norwegian bishop and politician, [[Minister of Education and Research (Norway)|Norwegian Minister of Education and Church Affairs]] (d. 1899)\n*[[1847]] &ndash; [[Otto Wallach]], German chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1931)\n*[[1851]] &ndash; [[Ruperto Chap\u00ed]], Spanish composer, co-founded [[Sociedad General de Autores y Editores]] (d. 1909)\n*  1851   &ndash; [[Vincent d'Indy]], French composer and educator (d. 1931)\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[Jan van Beers (artist)|Jan van Beers]], Belgian painter and illustrator (d. 1927)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[Giovanni Battista Grassi]], Italian physician, zoologist, and entomologist (d. 1925)\n*[[1855]] &ndash; [[William Libbey]], American target shooter, colonel, mountaineer, geographer, geologist, and  archaeologist (d. 1927)\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Karl Pearson]], English mathematician, eugenicist, and academic (d. 1936)\n*[[1859]] &ndash; [[George Giffen]], Australian cricketer and footballer (d. 1927)\n*[[1860]] &ndash; [[Frank Frost Abbott]], American-Swiss scholar and academic (d. 1924)\n*[[1862]] &ndash; [[Jelena Dimitrijevi\u0107]], Serbian short story writer, novelist, poet, traveller, social worker, feminist and polyglot (d. 1945)\n*  1862   &ndash; [[Arturo Berutti]], Argentinian composer (d. 1938)\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[Henry Royce]], English engineer and businessman, founded [[Rolls-Royce Limited]] (d. 1933)\n*[[1866]] &ndash; [[John Allan (Australian politician)|John Allan]], Australian politician, 29th [[Premier of Victoria]] (d. 1936)\n*[[1868]] &ndash; [[Patty Hill]], American songwriter and educator (d. 1946)\n*[[1869]] &ndash; [[James McNeill]], Irish politician, 2nd [[Governor-General of the Irish Free State]] (d. 1938)\n*  1869   &ndash; [[J. R. Clynes]], English trade unionist and politician, [[Home Secretary]] (d. 1949)\n*[[1871]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Mann]], German author and poet (d. 1950)\n*  1871   &ndash; [[Joseph G. Morrison]], American captain and Nazarene minister (d. 1939)\n*  1871   &ndash; [[Piet Aalberse]], Dutch politician, [[Ministry of Social Affairs and Employment (Netherlands)|Minister of Labour]] (d. 1948)\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Albert Marquet]], French painter (d. 1947)\n*[[1877]] &ndash; [[Oscar Gr\u00e9goire]], Belgian water polo player and swimmer (d. 1947)\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Kathleen Scott]], British sculptor (d. 1947)\n*[[1879]] &ndash; [[S\u00e1ndor Garbai]], Hungarian politician, 19th [[Prime Minister of Hungary]] (d. 1947)\n*  1879   &ndash; [[Miller Huggins]], American baseball player and manager (d. 1929)\n*  1879   &ndash; [[Edward Steichen]], Luxembourger-American painter and photographer (d. 1973)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Arkady Averchenko]], Russian playwright and satirist (d. 1925)\n*[[1882]] &ndash; [[Thomas Graham Brown]], Scottish mountaineer and physiologist (d. 1965)\n*[[1883]] &ndash; [[Marie Under]], Estonian author and poet (d. 1980)\n*[[1884]] &ndash; [[Gordon Thomson (rower)|Gordon Thomson]], English rower and lieutenant (d. 1953)\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Julio Lozano D\u00edaz]], Honduran accountant and politician, 40th [[President of Honduras]] (d. 1957)\n*  1885   &ndash; [[Reginald Fletcher, 1st Baron Winster]], English navy officer and politician, [[Secretary of State for Transport]] (d. 1961)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Sergey Kirov]], Russian politician (d. 1934)\n*  1886   &ndash; [[Wladimir Burliuk]], Ukrainian painter and illustrator (d. 1917)\n*  1886   &ndash; [[Ludwig Mies van der Rohe]], German-American architect, designed [[IBM Plaza]] and [[Seagram Building]] (d. 1969)\n*[[1887]] &ndash; [[V\u00e4in\u00f6 Siikaniemi]], Finnish javelin thrower, poet, and translator (d. 1932)\n*[[1888]] &ndash; [[George Alfred Lawrence Hearne]], English-South African cricketer (d. 1978)\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[Yakup Kadri Karaosmano\u011flu]], Egyptian-Turkish journalist, author, and politician (d. 1974)\n*  1889   &ndash; [[Leonard Mociulschi]], Romanian general (d. 1979)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Harald Julin]], Swedish swimmer and water polo player (d. 1967)\n*  1890   &ndash; [[Frederick Dalrymple-Hamilton]], Scottish admiral (d. 1974)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Lajos Zilahy]], Hungarian novelist and playwright (d. 1974)\n*  1891   &ndash; [[Klawdziy Duzh-Dushewski]], Belarusian-Lithuanian architect, journalist, and diplomat, created the [[Flag of Belarus]] (d. 1959)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Ferde Grof\u00e9]], American pianist and composer (d. 1972)\n*  1892   &ndash; [[Thorne Smith]], American author (d. 1934)\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[Karl Mannheim]], Hungarian-English sociologist and academic (d. 1947)\n*  1893   &ndash; [[G. Lloyd Spencer]], American lieutenant and politician (d. 1981)\n*  1893   &ndash; [[George Beranger]], Australian-American actor and director (d. 1973)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 Fonck]], French colonel and pilot (d. 1953)\n*[[1895]] &ndash; [[Roland Leighton]], English soldier and poet (d. 1915)\n*[[1897]] &ndash; [[Douglas Hartree]], English mathematician and physicist (d. 1958)\n*  1897   &ndash; [[Fred Keating]], American magician, stage and film actor (d. 1961)\n*[[1899]] &ndash; [[Francis Ponge]], French poet and author (d. 1988)\n*  1899   &ndash; [[Herbert Arthur Stuart]], German-Swiss physicist and academic (d. 1974)\n*  1899   &ndash; [[Gloria Swanson]], American actress and producer (d. 1983)\n*[[1901]] &ndash; [[Carl Barks]], American illustrator and screenwriter (d. 2000)\n*  1901   &ndash; [[Erich Ollenhauer]], German politician (d. 1963)\n*  1901   &ndash; [[Eisaku Sat\u014d]], Japanese politician, 61st [[Prime Minister of Japan]], [[Nobel Peace Prize|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 1975)\n*  1901   &ndash; [[Kenneth Slessor]], Australian journalist and poet (d. 1971)\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Sidney Buchman]], American screenwriter and producer (d. 1975)\n*  1902   &ndash; [[Charles Lang]], American cinematographer (d. 1998)\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Xavier Villaurrutia]], Mexican poet and playwright (d. 1950)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Leroy Carr]], American singer-songwriter and pianist (d. 1935)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Rudolf Christoph Freiherr von Gersdorff]], German general (d. 1980)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Elsie MacGill]], Canadian-American author and engineer (d. 1980)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Pee Wee Russell]], American clarinet player, saxophonist, and composer (d. 1969)\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Golo Mann]], German historian and author (d. 1994)\n*  1909   &ndash; [[Ben Webster]], American saxophonist (d. 1973)\n*  1909   &ndash; [[Valery Marakou]], Belarusian poet and translator (d. 1937)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[Ai Qing]], Chinese poet and author (d. 1996)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Veronika Tushnova]], Russian poet and physician (d. 1965)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[James Callaghan]], English lieutenant and politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. 2005)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Theodor Dannecker]], German [[SS]] officer (d. 1945)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Richard Denning]], American actor (d. 1998)\n*  1914   &ndash; [[Budd Schulberg]], American author, screenwriter, and producer (d. 2009)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Robert Lockwood, Jr.]], American guitarist (d. 2006)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Cyrus Vance]], American lawyer and politician, 57th [[United States Secretary of State]] (d. 2002)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Colin Rowe]], English-American architect, theorist and academic (d. 1999)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Phil Chess]], Czech-American record producer, co-founded [[Chess Records]] (d. 2016)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Moacir Barbosa Nascimento]], Brazilian footballer and coach (d. 2000)\n*  1921   &ndash; [[Harold Nicholas]], American actor and dancer (d. 2000)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Dick King-Smith]], English author (d. 2011)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Stefan Wul]], French author and surgeon (d. 2003)\n*  1922   &ndash; [[Jules Olitski]], Ukrainian-American painter, printmaker, and sculptor (d. 2007)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Sh\u016bsaku End\u014d]], Japanese author (d. 1996)\n*  1923   &ndash; [[Louis Simpson]], Jamaican-American poet, translator, and academic (d. 2012)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[Sarah Vaughan]], American singer (d. 1990)\n*  1924   &ndash; [[Ian Black (footballer, born 1924)|Ian Black]], Scottish international footballer, goalkeeper and lawn bowls player (d. 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/players/ian-black-23018/|title=Ian Black|website=11v11.com|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*  1924   &ndash; [[Margaret K. Butler]], American mathematician and computer programmer (d. 2013)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Frank O'Hara]], American writer (d. 1966)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Sylvia Anderson]], English voice actress, screenwriter, and producer (d. 2016)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Anthony Lewis]], American journalist and academic (d. 2013)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Mstislav Rostropovich]], Russian cellist and conductor (d. 2007)\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Jean Dotto]], French cyclist (d. 2000)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Anne Ramsey]], American actress (d. 1988)\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Reg Evans]], Australian actor (d. 2009)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[Daniel Spoerri]], Romanian-Swiss photographer, writer and artist\n*[[1931]] &ndash; [[David Janssen]], American actor and screenwriter (d. 1980)\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Junior Parker]], American singer and harmonica player (d. 1971)\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Bailey Olter]], Micronesian politician, 3rd [[President of the Federated States of Micronesia]] (d. 1999)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[L\u00ea V\u0103n H\u01b0ng]], South Vietnamese Brigadier general (d. 1975)\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Istv\u00e1n Csurka]], Hungarian journalist, author, and politician (d. 2012)\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Stanley Rother]], American Roman Catholic priest and missionary (d. 1981)\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Julian Glover]], English actor\n*[[1936]] &ndash; [[Malcolm Goldstein]], American violinist and composer\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Alan Hawkshaw]], English keyboard player and songwriter \n*[[1939]] &ndash; [[Jay Kim]], South Korean-American engineer and politician\n*  1939   &ndash; [[Cale Yarborough]], American race car driver and businessman\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Sandro Munari]], Italian race car driver\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Austin Pendleton]], American actor, director, and playwright\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Ivan Ga\u0161parovi\u010d]], Slovak lawyer and politician, 3rd [[President of Slovakia]]\n*  1941   &ndash; [[Liese Prokop]], Austrian pentathlete and politician, [[Federal Ministry of the Interior (Austria)|Austrian Minister of the Interior]] (d. 2006)\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[Michael Jackson (writer)|Michael Jackson]], English journalist and author (d. 2007)\n*  1942   &ndash; [[John Sulston]], English biologist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2018) \n*